      <div class="small-12 columns">
        <p>There were several design decisions made while coding of the webcrawler. When iterating through the websites it was tempting to use either an array of hashes or an array of objects. Both were considered because they contain a list of attributes stored within a single unit. However, an array of objects was chosen because it would have scalability. It’s significantly easier to manipulate objects as opposed to hashes.</p>
        <p>Ruby gems are useful for adding additional functionality with ease. Nokogiri is a gem (another name for Ruby library) that allows Ruby to parse through XML/HTML or similar markup languages. It was used to extract betting odds, usernames, and items being bet from the page during a set extraction interval. The extracted data was stored on the cloud, so the user could amass data on betting statistics.</p>
        <p>XPath was used to select the elements from the page. I extensively used Chrome’s developer tools to navigate through the DOM (Document Object Model). The DOM is particularly useful to understand the structure of the website. HTML, CSS, and JavaScript can all be used within the DOM to manipulate the site client-side.</p>
